I've decided to set up the "first two verses" as prose. On the basis of what Fleet and others have read of the first four lines, there is in my opinion no particular reason to think they are in verse, nor to think that they are exactly two verses. Fleet and most others since him have identified the "second verse" as sragdharā, which seems impossible given the prosody and distribution of the legible fragments (in l4, we'd need 10 syllables in the 6-character lacuna [or 11 if there's no lost syllable at the beginning of the line], and 8 syllables in the 3-character lacuna). The little that remains of the first two lines may in fact belong to a sragdharā verse, and it would be logical to have the second verse in the same metre as the preceding one and several following ones - but if lines 3-4 contain a sragdharā, then the readings are wrong and/or the verse halves do not coincide with the physical lines, as they do in subsequent verses. (I can't work the pattern out with mandākrāntā either, nor with any other metre. There may also be more than 2 verses in these 4 lines.) I think it's best, at least pending a chance of autopsy, to show these lines as prose. This entails that we'll have to number the verses differently than predecessors.
--></p>
